description: Here is the species list from the Echo Summit foray in South Lake Tahoe, CA. This is a yearly event put on by the Fungus Fed. of Santa Cruz, and many thanks to the organizers, which put on a great weekend for all invovled. But the weekend was a bad one for mushroom hunting, it was very dry, and there were more dried out species found than fresh ones. But still almost 40 species were found fresh enough to id., although I was told on a normal year it would be over 60, and 100 on a good year.

Ok, this one… got into a bit of discussion on this one. In the past these had been id’ed as hypothejus, and maybe they are. But there is a lot of overlap between hypothejus and d. v. californicus in the Agaricales of CA., a lot. In the end the discription of d. v. c. matched these just fine, while for hypothejus these fall into the sometimes looking catagory.

Mostly I am going to call them d. v. ca. as a kinda challenge to Hygrophorus experts out there. If the descriptions in the guides are so close, and really there were very few details that one had the other didn’t (I think only lactifers present or absent…), then how are these two species determined? In the original notes on d. v. ca. it states that the material has only been seen in northern Sierras above 5000 ft., and in Jackson St. forest in Mendocino Co. Which is where I have seen these, so I’m going for it for now, until an expert can point out the difference.

Found under conifers in the Echo Summit area, south of South Lake Tahoe. In a forested area near a large grassy clearing. The center of the grassy clearing was a seepage area, but this was 50-100 yards from where these were found.

The spot on the pores in the second shot was from KOH, which stained the pores a yellow brown.

7/16/2008 – Getting back to this one. I’m not a polypore type of guy, partially because I was taught most of what I know from Dennis Desjardin, and he is not a polypore type of guy, and also because I just don’t find that many of these. In this case, this is the only Boletopsis I’ve found anywhere, so its not something I know much about.

But this observation has been picked up by “Mushroom the Journal of Wild Mushrooming”, and was noted as interesting by Leon Shernoff there. Part of the interest was the “orange” color of the cap.

As part of this, I’ve gone back to the original photos and I’ve done a more careful color correction. Maybe this has reduced the “orange” color, I’m not sure, to me it didn’t have much of an orange in the first place. Not like some Lactarius or Hygrocybe, now those are orange. But perhaps for Boletopsis slight shadings are important. In any case, this does spark some interest in these, and it would good to find more and see what things look like in comparison.

Anyway, the initial comment was that as an orange Boletopsis this is a rare siting of B. skamaniensis (MtJoWM vol. 25 no. 4) , which in further comments this was equated with Albatrellus skamanius (MtJoWM vol. 26 no.1). The further comments go on to say that A. skamanius is more known from the NW, and was very rare, but with further study has been seen from more places now, and they site a paper. But with an orange color from the Sierras this is more probably Boletopsis smithii.

He mentions that B. smithii is about 2 inches in size, and these were 3-4 inches in size.

He mentions that at the foray it was interesting that this specimen seems to have been brushed off as just another weird color variant. I don’t think it was that conscious, it was more, hey looks like a Boletopsis? You know anything about Boletopsis? Nope not me, what does Arora say, don’t know it looks like B. subsquamosa is what he suggests. Great, close enough for me, lets keep going…

I would like to thank the comments in “Mushroom the Journal” from Leon Shernoff and Jim Ginns about this observation, there is a number of interesting things about Albatrellus and Boletopsis mentioned in the articles, and I will make an effort to be careful about Boletopsis that I find in the future. (Since I didn’t put much care into finding this one…)

Found this on a Eucalyptus near my house, it comes up each year in the same place about this time. It is kinda the first mushroom I find, and it tells me the season is starting.

This one is a view of the fresh mushroom, it grew to be about twice this size, and flattened out into layered fans. And now, Oct. 12, about two weeks later it is just dried out and light tan.

This was one of the mountain lions studied as part of the long-term monitoring program conducted by the NPS in the Santa Monica Mountains. Unfortunately, this 2 year old male was killed by his father, likely due to territory constraints. I helped carry this cat out of the mountains and was able to attend its necropsy.

description: guessing these prints we saw some years ago were black bear prints. Found on JMT south of Garnet lake- black bear country.
observed near a small body of water near the pass coming out of Garnet Lake in the Sierras on the John Muir Trail.  somewhere around 9900 feet altitude.

1/3 female, pausing after a long session of solo ovipositing.

2/3 same specimen, detail of genitalia. 

3/3 genitalia of a different ovipositing female. 

In our area these females oviposit: 1) coupled with the male after copulation; 2) with the male hovering above; 3) solo. They do not brush their tails in water to brush off eggs in the usual manner; rather, they fly among the rushes at the pond margins and drop eggs from about 2-4 feet onto dried mud. The eggs then have to survive until the following spring when the pond level rises again. I find this species only at ponds that dry up, partially or completely. The strategy must work because this is a very abundant species. This pond is normally completely dry by mid-autumn.

I could share more interesting observations about this species but this site does not appear to be a good place for discussion of behavior.

A male Pacific Spiketail preys on yellowjackets and is in turn attacked by female yellowjackets, which causes some annoyance but does not change the outcome.

I have found males of this species in chaparral, far from water; in our area it seems to prey exclusively on yellowjackets.

description:
1/5 Black Saddlebags tandem ovipositing. By remaining coupled the male ensures other males do not inseminate the female. In some species the male hovers above, guarding, while the female oviposits.

2/5 In the Anisoptera, the male’s cerci grip the female behind the eyes, with his epiproct in front and between them. Often the male loses interest after a while and females are seen ovipositing solo.

3/5 The Black Saddlebags male releases the female for oviposition; she swipes the tip of her abdomen in the water brushing off an egg or eggs; he then reseizes her. This image shows the moment of release.

4/5 The male grabs the female first with his legs, then transfers the grip to his terminal appendages. The drop-and-grab take only a fraction of a second; the transfer is not normally visible, but one might surmise that in general this is the way male dragonflies seize females.

5/5 The pair flies on in tandem position. What appears to be an egg mass is visible at the female’s tail end.

description:
this neat, unusual species of ash is very different from others of its genus.  It grows as a tall emergent 'wispy' shrub in dry chaparral environments, and it loses its leaves halfway through the warm dry season rather than the cold season.  It's relatively unusual though not endangered.

(note that the ash is the yellow-leaved species on this hillside)
